EPIC 21 — Regulatory Compliance (EU Data Boundaries, GDPR, HIPAA)
Goal
Ensure the platform meets strict regulatory requirements for handling personal and health data across the EU and US, including data residency, consent, privacy rights, and secure processing.

1. EU Data Residency & Data Boundaries
User Stories
As a European nutritionist, I want all my patient data stored exclusively within the EU so I can comply with local regulations.

As an admin, I want to enforce regional data boundaries so data never leaves the EU without explicit consent.

As a system architect, I want to ensure backups, logs, and analytics also remain within EU‑approved regions.

Acceptance Criteria
All primary and secondary storage located in EU regions (Azure West Europe/North Europe).

No cross‑region replication unless explicitly configured.

Data processing by sub‑processors restricted to EU‑approved regions.

2. GDPR — Lawful Basis & Consent
User Stories
As a patient, I want to give explicit consent for data processing so I understand how my data is used.

As a nutritionist, I want to record and manage patient consent so I can comply with GDPR.

As a patient, I want to withdraw consent at any time so I can control my personal data.

Acceptance Criteria
Consent stored with timestamp, version, and purpose.

Withdrawal triggers automatic revocation of access and optional data deletion.

Consent logs immutable and exportable.

3. GDPR — Right to Access (Art. 15)
User Stories
As a patient, I want to request a copy of all my data so I can review what is stored about me.

Acceptance Criteria
Export includes: profile, consultations, meal plans, messages, documents, logs.

Export delivered in machine‑readable format (JSON/CSV/PDF bundle).

Delivered within legally required timeframe.

4. GDPR — Right to Erasure (Art. 17)
User Stories
As a patient, I want to request deletion of my data so I can exercise my privacy rights.

Acceptance Criteria
Soft‑delete workflow for legal retention periods.

Full purge after retention expires.

Audit log preserved but anonymized.

5. GDPR — Data Minimization & Purpose Limitation
User Stories
As an admin, I want the system to collect only necessary data so we comply with GDPR principles.

Acceptance Criteria
No unnecessary fields in patient profiles.

Optional fields clearly marked.

Analytics uses anonymized or pseudonymized data.

6. GDPR — Data Processing Agreements
User Stories
As a business owner, I want DPAs available so I can legally onboard clients.

Acceptance Criteria
DPA templates available for download.

Signed DPAs stored per account.

Sub‑processor list published and versioned.

7. HIPAA — PHI Protection
User Stories
As a US nutritionist, I want PHI stored securely so I comply with HIPAA.

As an admin, I want audit trails for all PHI access so I can detect unauthorized access.

Acceptance Criteria
Encryption in transit (TLS 1.2+) and at rest (AES‑256).

Role‑based access control (RBAC) with least privilege.

Full audit logs: who accessed what, when, and from where.

Automatic log retention for minimum 6 years.

Business Associate Agreement (BAA) available.

8. HIPAA — Breach Notification
User Stories
As an admin, I want automated breach detection so I can respond quickly.

Acceptance Criteria
Alerts for anomalous access patterns.

Incident response workflow documented.

Notification templates for affected users.

9. Data Encryption & Key Management
User Stories
As a security engineer, I want centralized key management so encryption is consistent.

Acceptance Criteria
Keys stored in HSM (Azure Key Vault).

Key rotation policies enforced.

No plaintext secrets in logs or code.

10. Privacy by Design & Default
User Stories
As a product owner, I want all new features to undergo privacy review so we maintain compliance.

Acceptance Criteria
DPIA required for new modules.

Privacy checklist integrated into development workflow.

Feature flags used to isolate sensitive features.

11. Data Retention Policies
User Stories
As an admin, I want configurable retention rules so I can meet local legal requirements.

Acceptance Criteria
Retention per data type (consultations, messages, documents).

Automatic cleanup jobs.

Retention logs for auditing.

12. Secure Data Transfer
User Stories
As a system architect, I want secure APIs so data is protected during integration.

Acceptance Criteria
OAuth2 / OpenID Connect for authentication.

No PHI in URL parameters.

Rate limiting and anomaly detection.
